leden","1365–Male":"1365–Overleden","1420–Female":"1420–Overleden","1390–Male":"1390–Overleden","1339–1385":"1339–1385","1327–1387":"1327–1387","1385":"1385","1390":"1390","Abt February 1367":"circa februari 1367","1327":"1327","ABT 1363":"circa 1363","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","1339":"1339","of Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Henhull, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt February 1367–Deceased":"about February 1367–Deceased","1364–1388":"1364–1388","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1366–1398":"1366–1398","1367–Female":"1367–Deceased","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","1420–Female":"1420–Deceased","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1339–1385":"1339–1385","1327–1387":"1327–1387","1385":"1385","1390":"1390","Abt February 1367":"about February 1367","1327":"1327","ABT 1363":"about 1363","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1420":"1420","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","1339":"1339","of Henhull, Cheshire, England":"Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Henhull was born about February 1367, in Henhull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard de Henhull Esquire, was 29 and her mother, Elen Worleston, was 41. She married Richard de Golborne about 1389, in Golborne, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt February 1367–Deceased":"umbes veebruar 1367–Surnud","1364–1388":"1364–1388","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1366–1398":"1366–1398","1367–Female":"1367–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1339–1385":"1339–1385","1327–1387":"1327–1387","1385":"1385","1390":"1390","Abt February 1367":"umbes